spirituality, wisdom, and land-based knowledge is critical to human survival in the face of environmental destruction and human-induced climate change. Reinterpreting world history from an Indigenous perspective, Stonechild’s solution to this unfolding catastrophe is “ecolization,” a state in which humans recognize they are not the central purpose of creation and a way of existing harmoniously with the natural and spiritual worlds. Beautifully written, urgent, and critical, Challenge to Civilization reminds us that it is not Earth that is in danger of extinction, but ourselves, and Indigenous spiritual wisdom can be the guiding light through what will otherwise be humanity’s final, ever-darkening days.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspects. 0aHuman ecology. 0aIndigenous peoplesxIntellectual life. 0aSustainability. 0aTraditional ecological knowledge. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  aAboriginal.  aAmerica.  aChina.  aCreator.  aCree.  aDalits.  aIndigenous.  aManitou.  aStonechild.  aTaoism.  aUNDRIP.  aVatican.  aallies.  aancient.  aanxiety.  aapocalypse.  acivilization.  aclimate.  aeconomics.  aeducation.  aelders.  aenvironment.  afuture.  ahumanity.  ainternational.  amental illness.  anature.  anihilism.  aontology.  aparadigm.  aphilosophy.  aprophecy.  apsychology.  areconciliation.  areform.  areligion.  aresidential school.  arespect.  aspirituality.  astewardship.  asurvival.  atechnology.  auniversities.  awetiko.  awisdom.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088977982240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889779822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889779822/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles